  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Strict reporting requirements\n- Aggressive criminal prosecution\n- Focus on financial institution compliance\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified regulatory framework\n- Emphasis on preventative measures\n- Centralized financial intelligence units\n- Strong international cooperation\n- Detailed customer due diligence requirements\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Sophisticated legal framework\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Enhanced financial monitoring\n- Robust asset recovery mechanisms\n- Significant focus on transparency\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historical banking secrecy laws\n- Gradual shift towards international transparency\n- Strict financial regulations\n- Cooperative international stance\n- Advanced compliance mechanisms\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict control of financial transactions\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n- Growing emphasis on international standards\n- State-controlled financial oversight\n\n6. Russia\n- Developing legal framework\n- Inconsistent enforcement\n- Complex regulatory environment\n- Limited international cooperation\n- Significant challenges in implementation\n\nThese comparative perspectives demonstrate varying legal approaches to combating money laundering.",
